 - (tensor of) labels (string) and
 - **(sequence of) probabilities (map of string to float).**

We have a workaround that uses integer labels.

- JDK 11.0.4
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.6.0, CPU
- Python version: 3.8.5


body:
**Describe the bug**
The ArmNN execution provider has numerous issues with its setup.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Raspberry Pi 4 with Raspian OS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): Source
- ONNX Runtime version: Latest

**Issues**

- Build instructions for ArmNN EP in the ORT [Build.MD](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/BUILD.md#ArmNN) could be more helpful.
  -  [These](https://developer.arm.com/solutions/machine-learning-on-arm/developer-material/how-to-guides/configuring-the-arm-nn-sdk-build-environment-for-onnx/single-page) instructions seem to be much better at providing instructions of getting into a state where you can build against libarmnn, but have some issues
     - Needs newer protobuf version than specified
       - https://github.com/ARM-software/armnn/issues/476
     - When building for usage with ORT should probably use onnx.proto from ORT instead of an arbitrary ONNX commit so they match. Additionally ArmNN is using protobuf full and ORT is using protobuf-lite
       - Can comment out `option optimize_for = LITE_RUNTIME;` in cmake/external/onnx/onnx/onnx.proto if creating the proto files used in the build on ArmNN with that as input
       - unknown if using protobuf on one side and protobuf-lite on the other is likely to cause any runtime issues
  - `./build.sh --use_armnn --armnn_home /path/to/ComputeLibrary --armnn_libs /path/to/build` is incorrect. `--armnn_home` should be the path to armnn not ComputeLibrary 
- Building also needs the ARM ComputeLibrary include and library directories
  - this can be specified with `--acl_home` and `--acl_libs`, but cmake/onnxruntime_providers.cmake needs updating so that `${onnxruntime_ACL_HOME}` and `${onnxruntime_ACL_HOME}/include` are included [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/onnxruntime_providers.cmake#L922) when building onnxruntime_providers_armnn 
- CMakeLists.txt adds armnn (and acl for that matter) using `link_library`. This adds them to all binaries, including ones that have no dependency on armnn (e.g. the standalone MLAS test exe onnxruntime_mlas_test). As the libraries are added to onnxruntime_EXTERNAL_LIBRARIES they most likely do not need to be also added using link_library.
  -  [Here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L750) and [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L792) can probably be removed
- The way that libarmnn.so is added doesn't seem to be carrying through paths correctly leading to `cannot find -larmnn` link errors.
  - changing the find_library call [here]( https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L788-L790) to do the same as [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L778-L781) with an add_library/set_target_properties combination seems to work
-  onnxruntime_perf_test needs an update to link using onnxruntime_EXTERNAL_LIBRARIES [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/cmake/onnxruntime_unittests.cmake#L825-L827) as well so that the arm libraries are added correctly there.
- [/onnxruntime/core/providers/armnn/math/gemm.h](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/91b19b836451db2f0faa1733f2f14ba3408b1ada/onnxruntime/core/providers/armnn/math/gemm.h#L10) needs to include gemm_helper.h as well as gemm.h so that GemmHelper is defined
  - Add `#include "core/providers/cpu/math/gemm_helper.h"`

**Description**
This pull request implements part of the paper on [Data-Free Quantization Through Weight Equalization and Bias Correction](https://arxiv.org/pdf/1906.04721.pdf) by Nagel et al. 2019, specifically the equalization algorithm.

**Motivation and Context**
Equalization shows improved performance in data-free quantization in models that see performance loss in depth-wise convolutions. In the reference model, equalization improves IntegerOps accuracy by roughly 10% and improves QLinearOps accuracy by roughly 20%. Both the algorithm and this example result are included.

I presented this work to Microsoft as an intern with Intel Corporation at the Microsoft Technology Center in Folsom, CA. Thank you @yufenglee for considering this request.

title: Don't send out Runtime error telemetry when can't create LearningModelDevice on machine without hardware adapters
body:
Runtime error telemetry should only be sent out for scenarios where WinML behaved in an unexpected incorrect way.

In the scenario, that there are no hardware adapters available and a LearningModelDevice targetting GPU can't be created, Runtime error telemetry shouldn't be sent but hresult error should still be returned to the client app.

TelemetryFallback callback function that calls LogRuntimeError for any failure can be removed for these reasons:
- WinML "THROW_IF_FAILED" macros already call LogRuntimeError, no need to send error telemetry twice.
- The telemetry data sent by this callback function doesn't contain line and file information.
- Having this prevents WinML from throwing error without sending telemetry.

title: Tile perf enhancements - continued
body:
**Description**: 

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/6376 introduced an optimization to the Tile kernels to process inputs where the net tiling effect is just multiple copies of the input buffer.

For example:
input shape = [1, 1, 256 * 50]
repeats = [1, 200, 1]
output shape = [1, 200, 256 * 50]

This worked well when there was no batching involved and the optimization didn't kick-in when batching was introduced.
As a slight extension, handle batching in this optimization.

For example:
input shape = [***5***, 1, 256 * 50]
repeats = [1, 200, 1]
output shape = [***5***, 200, 256 * 50]

In this case, we would copy each of the 5 sub-tensors in the batch 200 times.

Improves the perf of a 1PP model by ~30% (95 percentile) when batch size is 5.

**Motivation and Context**
Performance
